  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The concept of inertia originates from **Newton's First Law of Motion**, which states:\n\n*\u201cAn object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion continues in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an unbalanced external force.\u201d*\n\n**Inertia** is the property of an object that resists changes to its state of motion. Essentially, it's a measure of how much an object \u201cresists\u201d being accelerated when a force is applied.\n\n### Inertial Force\n\nWhen analyzing motion from a non-inertial (accelerating) reference frame, **inertial forces** (also known as fictitious or pseudo forces) appear to act on objects. These are not real forces arising from any physical interaction but are perceived due to the acceleration of the reference frame itself.\n\nThe **magnitude of the inertial force** (\\( F_{\\text{inertia}} \\)) experienced by an object can be calculated using Newton's Second Law:\n\n\\[\nF = m \\times a\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object.\n- \\( a \\) is the acceleration of the reference frame relative to an inertial frame.\n\nIn the context of inertial forces:\n\\[\nF_{\\text{inertia}} = -m \\times a\n\\]\n \nThe negative sign indicates that the inertial force acts in the opposite direction to the acceleration of the reference frame.\n\n### Example\n\n- **Scenario:** Imagine you're in a car that suddenly accelerates forward. From your perspective inside the car (a non-inertial frame), it feels like a force is pushing you backward into your seat.\n  \n- **Calculation:** If the car accelerates at \\( 3 \\, \\text{m/s}^2 \\) and you have a mass of \\( 70 \\, \\text{kg} \\), the inertial force you feel is:\n  \n  \\[\n  F_{\\text{inertia}} = 70 \\, \\text{kg} \\times 3 \\, \\text{m/s}^2 = 210 \\, \\text{N}\n  \\]\n  \n  This force acts opposite to the direction of the car\u2019s acceleration.\n\n### Key Points\n\n- **Inertial Force Magnitude:** \\( F = m \\times a \\)\n- **Direction:** Opposite to the acceleration of the reference frame.\n- **Nature:** Pseudo-force observed in non-inertial frames; no real physical interaction.\n\nUnderstanding inertial forces is crucial, especially in engineering and physics applications involving accelerating systems, such as vehicles, elevators, and rotating machinery.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The magnitude of the inertial force that a body applies on an object, due to its inertia, is calculated by multiplying the object's mass (\\( m \\)) by its acceleration (\\( a \\)). Therefore, the force is given by:\n\n\\[\nF = m \\times a\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( F \\) is the inertial force,\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object,\n- \\( a \\) is the acceleration.\n\nThis relationship succinctly captures how inertia resists changes in an object's motion.",
